<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-136-044 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 862 536</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  June 3 1991 v17 n11 p9(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Industry backs free trade pact. (electronic industry support forthe North American free trade agreement) (Business Trends)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Baatz, Elizabeth B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US electronics companies support the Bush administration'sproposed North American free trade agreement (FTA), which wouldmerge Mexico, the US and Canada into a single market that would belarger than the European Community.andP;  Adding Mexico to the 1988US-Canadian trade alliance would add only $6.5 billion to the $280billion US electronics industry, but the impact on individual USinterest groups would be much greater.andP;  Large US electronicscompanies would be able to invest in an emerging country and totake advantage of low wage rates, proximity and tax incentives inMexico.andP;  US labor unions oppose FTA because unskilled US laborers,who make an average of $14.32 an hour, would lose jobs to Mexicanworkers earning only $1.63 an hour.andP;  FTA is expected to cause anincrease in US electronics exports to Mexico from the $5 billionin exports shipped in 1990.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic IndustryNorth AmericaInternational TradeCooperative AgreementNational GovernmentMexicoUnited StatesCanadaIndustry AnalysisMarket Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Jobs and free trade: change in domestic employment. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>